<HEADLINE>
<P>
ON THE COVER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVEN LINAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Prime time is of the essence for Diane Sawyer. 
</P>
<P>
The former "60 Minutes" correspondent, who signed a reported $1.6-million 
annual pact with ABC in February, joins Sam Donaldson as co-anchor of the 
network's new "PrimeTime Live," a news magazine that debuts Thursday at 10 p.m. 
on Channels 7, 3, 10 and 42. 
</P>
<P>
Sawyer and Donaldson will host the series in front of a studio audience in New 
York. They will offer a mix of topical stories, investigative pieces and live 
reporting. As the title suggests, the programs will be live broadcasts, though 
viewers on the West Coast will see them on a tape-delay basis. 
</P>
<P>
And with NBC's "L.A. Law" and CBS' "Knots Landing" as competition come fall, 
ABC has done no favors for Sawyer and Donaldson. But who knows? Perhaps their 
time has come. . . . STEVEN LINAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, COLOR, (Cover) Diane Sawyer Moves into ABC's Prime Time 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
