<P>
An angry American Indian family closed what has been a public road, claiming 
that their ancestors never gave Madera County permission to use it. Echo Valley 
Road is the only access to about 100 homes in the Sierra Nevada near Oakhurst. 
Indian heirs of Frank Hammond formed a human barricade across the road and 
asked residents to sign a form absolving them of any liability for injuries 
that might happen on the 1,200-foot stretch they claim. Most residents signed 
the form, but some just drove through, saying that the Hammond heirs were 
legally wrong to try to land lock their properties. County Counsel Jeff Kuhn 
said the county has offered $10,000 for the right-of-way, which has been used 
as a public road since 1961, and is now considering condemnation proceedings to 
reopen the road. The $10,000 offer was called "a slap in the face," by Harold 
Hammond. "This is not about money," he said. "This is about principle. They 
took something from us, and they don't give a damn." 
