<HEADLINE>
<P>
OUTTAKES: THE AIDS STORY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By John M. Wilson 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Also from the AIDS file: A full page ad in the trade papers promoting a 
low-budget movie called "The Victims" has roused a response. The ad pictures a 
barechested man positioned sensually between two affectionate women under the 
slogan: If you don't want to catch AIDS go see 'The Victims'! 
</P>
<P>
Charles Cotayo, director of distribution for Florida-based Mochon International 
Film Distribution, said: "We've gotten so many calls from that ad, it's 
ridiculous" -- some from AIDS organizations expressing concern that the film 
might sensationalize its subject. 
</P>
<P>
Cotayo said the film concerns a successful Cuban emigre and family man in Miami 
whose idyllic life is shattered when the threat of AIDS looms after his 
impulsive act of infidelity. 
</P>
<P>
Cotayo called it a cautionary tale of "significant social value" that delivers 
a strong message about unsafe sex. "It's not a sensationalized, exploitative 
movie," he said. "It's reality." 
</P>
<P>
Cast with Florida actors, "The Victims" will get a trial release in south 
Florida on Sept. 15. John M. Wilson 
</P>
</TEXT>
